Multiple encryption means data is protected more than once using different algorithms or keys—like wrapping a message in several locked envelopes. Even if one layer is broken, the others stay secure. Common in layered defense or mix networks. It’s used in tools like onion routing, nested GPG encryption, and multi-hop proxies. Helps against targeted decryption or “harvest now, decrypt later” strategies. Look into terms like cascading ciphers, encryption chaining, envelope encryption, and hybrid crypto models. Each extra layer increases effort for attackers and reduces the risk that a single weak point exposes everything.